'''Edward Joseph (Eddie) Friel'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ascap.com/ace/search.cfm?requesttimeout=300&mode=results&searchstr=1161225&search_in=c&search_type=exact&search_det=t,s,w,p,b,v&results_pp=25&start=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310085150/http://www.ascap.com/ace/search.cfm?requesttimeout=300 |archivedate=2012-03-10 |df= }}</ref> was born in [[Belfast]] in 1962. He is a B. Mus. Honours graduate who in 1986 started his professional career as a [[music teacher]]. After one year he decided to pursue his talents as a musician and composer in local piano bars at home as well as in Canada and Europe, where he travelled for a year. He has toured with [[Van Morrison]] as a piano player and features extensively on Van Morrison's album ''Hymns to the Silence''.

In 1995 he represented Ireland in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] with the song "[[Dreamin' (Eddie Friel song)|Dreamin']]". The song finished a disappointing 14th place; Norway won the contest, breaking the three years Ireland staged the contest.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061121101222/http://www.esctoday.com/annual/1995/page/3 ]</ref>

